00:04:00.639 --> 00:04:08.639
They fund a lot of infrastructure projects around the world, primarily in developing countries in Latin America.

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:22.640
And they wanted to mine lending agreements and infrastructure proposals in order to better evaluate the riskiness of those projects and of those funding packages.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:29.640
They said, all we have are PDF style documents that describe the terms of those loan agreements.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:49.640
Can you help us extract data from them in a standard way and then help us build a risk model such that when new organizations apply for funding grants or loans effectively for infrastructure projects, we have a better framework for determining whether or not they're high risk and therefore what the appropriate monitoring structures and levers need to be.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:54.640
So we built a bespoke tool for them that did exactly that.

00:04:54.640 --> 00:05:09.640
It connected to a large repository of infrastructure proposals and associated loan documents, extracted key terms, and then looked at the historical outcomes of those projects in order to build a risk model and say,

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:18.640
here are the key factors and elements inside those loan packages and inside the effectively project plans that help us forecast what is the likely outcome.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:24.640
Is a project going to be over time, over budget? What is the likelihood of success? And so on and so forth.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:40.640
As a result, we developed an application that they could pull up on their desktops and rerun the workflow to load, extract additional information, loan information from documents, and then price subsequent loans.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:57.640
This type of use case of leveraging natural language processing plus machine learning in order to arrive at a risk model is something that we're seeing happen with increased frequency across the financial services space.

