But a lot of times this term is used in a nebulous way.

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:35.640
And so one of the pieces that we've found to be most helpful is to be able to define a little bit better, what does it actually mean to be data driven?

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:41.640
How do you know if you're data driven and how can you identify the key pieces to work on within the organization?

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:45.640
So the way that we've identified that is across two different axes.

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:54.640
We have our data literacy, which is the overall knowledge as well as the governance and oversight within an organization.

00:24:55.640 --> 00:25:06.640
And then also the data infrastructure, which, especially in finance, is crucial to ensure that data is accessible appropriately and that it's also stored securely.

00:25:08.640 --> 00:25:13.640
So thinking about data infrastructure, we've identified these three pillars.

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:17.640
Data collection, data storage and data access.

00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:27.640
So in terms of data collection, you know, I saw a lot of evidence about the data that folks are using with its customer transactions, CRM data, student data.

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:32.640
So presumably there's some collection that happens on a continuous basis.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:34.640
If not, that's definitely something to look into.

00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:42.640
But even more importantly, making sure that the data is collected in a way that is then easy to analyze and to store.

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:44.640
Is also pretty crucial.

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:50.640
So if you have a bunch of data that's disorganized, maybe there's a lot of missing values that makes it a lot more difficult to pull insights from it.

00:25:51.640 --> 00:26:02.640
So ensuring that the data collection that you have is not only collected in a timely manner, but then also stored well and then stored in a way that makes it easy to pull insights from.

00:26:03.640 --> 00:26:05.640
The second pillar is data storage.

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:17.640
I think everyone on this call, especially if you're in the finance industry, understands a lot of the information that you're dealing with is personal information, whether that's credit scores, spending histories, bank account information.

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:22.640
Ensuring that your data is stored securely is paramount to that.

00:26:23.640 --> 00:26:37.640
But at the same time, the third pillar, data access, is also very impactful because if your teams cannot access the data that they need to make timely decisions, then that makes it difficult to use.

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:42.640
And that makes it difficult to use the actual data that you've collected.

00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:49.640
So, you know, you can start to ask yourself, the data sources that you're using now, is it easy for you to access?

00:26:49.640 --> 00:26:51.640
Is it easy for your colleagues to access?

00:26:52.640 --> 00:27:04.640
If you have these types of questions, you know, those types of questions are ones you should be asking yourself in order to make sure that this is available to you.

00:27:08.640 --> 00:27:11.640
And then on the other axis, we have data literacy.

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:20.640
And with this, you know, one of the biggest challenges that we see is a communication gap between the data and the non-data professionals within an organization.

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:26.640
So becoming a more data-driven organization really starts from the top, and that's in terms of data leadership.

00:27:27.640 --> 00:27:31.640
Do executives actually champion data utilization?

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:43.640
I would say most do, but maybe they don't understand the resources that they need to allocate or the time they need to give people to better understand how to use data.

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:54.640
So if you have a data champion in your organization, if you have one person who is helping set that data strategy, then that's a good sign that your leadership is taking this very seriously.

00:27:55.640 --> 00:27:58.640
The second pillar that we have under data literacy is data governance.

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:06.640
So I think especially in finance, you probably have a lot of guidelines where you can access the data, how you can access the data, who can see the data.

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:10.640
Do you have these guidelines somewhere?

00:28:11.640 --> 00:28:12.640
Does everybody have access to them?

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:15.640
Are people using data in a way that's uniform to them?

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:25.640
So making sure that across the organization, people are using data in the same way so that it's easily accessible to all and easily transferable and readable.

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:41.640
So something simple or something straightforward, if you don't have a data dictionary in place, putting one in place already can help you ensure that all of your variables are defined in the same way, which makes it a lot easier to clean and then to analyze later.

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:44.640
Last piece is data knowledge.

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:48.640
Does your staff, do you, do your colleagues know how to ask the right questions about data?

00:28:49.640 --> 00:28:51.640
Do they understand how to interpret the insights about data?

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:58.640
Without that, it makes it really difficult to start to become more data driven and to use data to inform your insights.

00:28:59.640 --> 00:29:10.640
So, you know, a lot of ways that we address this is specifically about developing programs within organizations to help them become more data driven and to drive that continuous culture of learning.

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:17.640
So as I'm going through this, maybe you have some questions or maybe you've identified, hey, what's a key pain point?

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:26.640
Like, maybe there's data that you're unable to access, or maybe you're seeing that a lot of your colleagues are having difficulty asking questions about data.

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:33.640
You know, one source of data that we see a lot are a bunch of Excel spreadsheets that are live on somebody's laptop.

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:37.640
And then the minute that person leaves, those Excel spreadsheets disappear, right?

00:29:37.640 --> 00:29:39.640
That's something that we refer to as dark data.

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:44.640
So this is something that can be ameliorated with data governance or data storage.

