00:36:35.639 --> 00:36:46.639
So before we finish up the presentation, this is an area that we always like to emphasize both in our training programs and also in our presentations, which is about the ethical use of data.

00:36:47.639 --> 00:36:50.639
So this is a case study that maybe some of you know.

00:36:51.639 --> 00:36:55.639
This was one that was done by Target.

00:36:56.639 --> 00:37:00.639
So essentially about 20 years ago at this point in time, Target had a lot of information.

00:37:01.639 --> 00:37:06.639
They're a huge retail store in the United States for those who might not live here.

00:37:07.639 --> 00:37:14.639
And they had a large customer base of data about purchases, past purchases.

00:37:14.639 --> 00:37:25.639
And wanted to start to predict which of their customers would be pregnant because they know that when an individual is pregnant, they tend to get more set in their habits.

00:37:26.639 --> 00:37:31.639
And if they can catch somebody during that stage, they tend to be more loyal customers throughout their life.

00:37:32.639 --> 00:37:43.639
So in order to do that, they had their data scientists sit for about two to multiple years of data to better understand, OK, which of their customers became pregnant.

00:37:44.639 --> 00:37:48.639
And then what were the key factors there that they can use to then predict who will become pregnant?

00:37:49.639 --> 00:37:51.639
So they did this analysis.

00:37:51.639 --> 00:37:57.639
And at the end of this analysis, they found some key indicators included buying ginger ale to help with nausea.

00:37:58.639 --> 00:38:07.639
Stopped buying wine was one of the factors that had a big correlation, as well as buying prenatal vitamins and things like that.

00:38:08.639 --> 00:38:13.639
And based on their predictions of who would become pregnant, they started to send out targeted flyers.

00:38:13.639 --> 00:38:19.639
And you'd think this is a great use case of data analytics and it is a demonstration of an effective use case.

00:38:20.639 --> 00:38:26.639
But what ended up happening is they sent one of these flyers to the parents of a 15 year old who hadn't told them that she was pregnant.

00:38:27.639 --> 00:38:32.639
So that became a big case that happened with a few other families as well.

00:38:33.639 --> 00:38:39.639
And it started to bring up the question of it's one thing to be able to mine customer data for insights.

00:38:39.639 --> 00:38:47.639
But how can you make sure you're using it in a way that doesn't cause harm, doesn't have ethical implications to it?

00:38:48.639 --> 00:38:56.639
So it's important, especially given that we're in the finance space, to think about how we're using customer data and how we need to be mindful of that fact.

00:38:57.639 --> 00:39:01.639
Now, interestingly enough, what Target ended up doing, it's not that they don't use that data for insights anymore.

00:39:02.639 --> 00:39:07.639
What happens is that they start to put lawnmowers next to baby cribs.

00:39:07.639 --> 00:39:12.639
So they just are a little bit more subtle about how they advertise that in the future.

00:39:13.639 --> 00:39:24.639
Speaking about ethical considerations, another one that's popped up, especially in the past few years, is about biases that exist in our current data that inform our models.

00:39:25.639 --> 00:39:28.639
So, again, it's our responsibility to ask these types of questions.

00:39:29.639 --> 00:39:34.639
There's one where it's, you know, how does the data reflect the society that we're in today?

00:39:34.639 --> 00:39:49.639
And if it does perpetuate any stereotypes or biases, how can we build models for future prediction or, for example, granting loans that will mitigate some of those biases and risks so that we don't perpetuate that?

00:39:50.639 --> 00:39:57.639
This is a difficult question. I'm spending a few minutes on it, whereas there's a much larger conversation to be had.

00:39:57.639 --> 00:40:25.639
But the important point to get across here is, as you are building these models, as you're involved in these models, make sure to ask these questions about, you know, accounting for biases before the data is being put into the model, making sure that the model accounts for that, and understanding how to mitigate that so that you can make the best decisions for your customers without introducing, you know, some biases that might already exist in the data.

00:40:25.639 --> 00:40:38.639
Last piece that I'll talk about is, you know, we talked a little bit about data infrastructure. Dimitri talked about a few case studies that he's seen.

00:40:39.639 --> 00:40:51.639
But on the other side, there's that data literacy component of that, and this is an example of how a lot of financial institutions today are starting to realize it's not only the infrastructure they need to have in place, but it's also the appropriate staff with those skills.

00:40:52.639 --> 00:41:01.639
So we've done a lot of work in the finance space with that. One of the use cases specifically is with Discover Financial Services, where they actually developed a pretty robust infrastructure.

00:41:02.639 --> 00:41:16.639
And what they realized is they had a lot of new hires coming in that maybe had some of the prerequisite skills with a good foundation, but not all of the skills that they wanted to, you know, that they needed in order to be effective.

00:41:17.639 --> 00:41:35.639
So we work with them to build an onboarding program that helped train them in R, as well as in other tools, including SQL and Snowflake, so that by the time that they left that onboarding process, they felt much more comfortable within the infrastructure that they had, so they could be much more effective off the bat.

00:41:36.639 --> 00:41:47.639
We see a lot of this happening, and it's not just the onboarding process, but because hiring is so difficult right now for data scientists, they're a rare breed, and I'd say especially in the finance industry, it can be really difficult.

00:41:48.639 --> 00:41:57.639
A lot of financial institutions are now turning to this training aspect, whether they're doing it internally or they're bringing somebody else in, to help develop that skill set across the organization.

