And I would have liked to know, because I know Python is also more and more used in the finance industry.

00:49:30.639 --> 00:49:38.639
And I would have liked to have your impression and feelings about how R and Python evolved or are adopting.

00:49:39.639 --> 00:49:52.639
And also the second question I asked, what do you think are the two or three other main languages that are entering the finance data driven analysis, please?

00:49:53.639 --> 00:49:54.639
Yeah, absolutely.

00:49:55.639 --> 00:50:05.639
So you're right in that the sort of Python user community has grown somewhat faster because it's grown on the backs of software engineers.

00:50:06.639 --> 00:50:12.639
For example, I started as an R user. And so that's still my first love as far as programming languages go.

00:50:13.639 --> 00:50:17.639
And I find that, for example, R's syntax tends to be simpler than that of Python.

00:50:18.639 --> 00:50:23.639
So if you have a software engineering background, picking up Python can be pretty trivial because you're already familiar with the notion of data structures.

00:50:24.639 --> 00:50:31.639
If you are starting from an Excel or sort of VBA background, then Python might look somewhat foreign and R is going to be a lot easier for you to adopt.

00:50:32.639 --> 00:50:37.639
Most people who are in finance actually started in some form of spreadsheet software, right?

00:50:38.639 --> 00:50:40.639
So to them, transitioning into R would actually be easier.

00:50:41.639 --> 00:50:53.639
And in my experience, R is going to give you just easier, faster options for prototyping, proving your point, doing the analysis, creating interactive visualization, standing up a light application with something like R Shiny.

00:50:54.639 --> 00:50:59.639
So I'm a huge fan of R, and that's the main language in which I program in.

00:50:59.639 --> 00:51:09.639
I don't think that the fact that there's been such a huge uptake in Python, for example, precludes another language like R from being just as widely used and helpful.

00:51:10.639 --> 00:51:14.639
Ultimately, I've learned it's about your personal preference and what gets the job done faster.

00:51:15.639 --> 00:51:16.639
Those two, I think, still dominate.

00:51:17.639 --> 00:51:23.639
There are going to be some languages that come into play when you're talking about scale systems, but I would attribute them less to finance.

00:51:23.639 --> 00:51:30.639
There's nothing about finance and the structure of a different language that make them better adapted to finance, right?

00:51:31.639 --> 00:51:37.639
But when you're talking about some scaled applications, especially for transaction processing, Scala is obviously important, right?

00:51:38.639 --> 00:51:50.639
But that has to do more due to its sort of software engineering and data piping capabilities rather than because it's better suited to finance in some way, shape, or form, in my experience.

00:51:53.639 --> 00:51:59.639
If I could ask you a bit more on that R versus Python.

00:52:00.639 --> 00:52:05.639
Even for us, we get into that situation or question quite often.

00:52:06.639 --> 00:52:21.639
Based on your experience, how do you find convincing or working with teams where the business side are very Excel, well-versed, and they might find R a lot more palatable.

00:52:21.639 --> 00:52:28.639
But the technology groups then come in and say, okay, no, we are not very comfortable with people using R.

00:52:29.639 --> 00:52:33.639
On the software side, there's a much bigger preference for Python.

00:52:34.639 --> 00:52:45.639
Working with clients or even within your organization and going through this maze of what should be encouraged or discouraged, or can you even have both of them working?

00:52:45.639 --> 00:52:53.639
And what kind of relationship should there be between R and Python or between business and technology people?

00:52:54.639 --> 00:52:56.639
How do you navigate conversations like those?

00:52:57.639 --> 00:53:07.639
Sure. So I would push on the word comfortable and who is comfortable with what and who is in the right lane in terms of being comfortable with what, right?

00:53:08.639 --> 00:53:12.639
Software engineering is going to be responsible for secured scale code.

00:53:12.639 --> 00:53:16.639
But the finance team is responsible for the analysis being correct, right?

00:53:17.639 --> 00:53:26.639
And so in my experience, the way that I see it is if you're writing a piece of code, you better be confident that it's working correctly from just a mathematical standpoint.

00:53:27.639 --> 00:53:33.639
And if the finance team is using R and is comfortable in R, then that has to be the code that actually runs the financial analysis.

00:53:34.639 --> 00:53:40.639
Now, there are lots of ways to call an R routine from Python and a Python routine from R.

00:53:40.639 --> 00:53:42.639
So they are interchangeable and lots of hooks around it.

00:53:43.639 --> 00:53:46.639
So it shouldn't be, you know, everybody must use one language or another language.

00:53:47.639 --> 00:53:50.639
There are lots of ways to make the two compatible.

00:53:51.639 --> 00:53:53.639
And in fact, we do that regularly in our line of work, right?

00:53:54.639 --> 00:53:57.639
There's a lot of packages that are just better in R than in Python and frankly, vice versa.

00:53:58.639 --> 00:53:59.639
And you shouldn't limit yourself to one or the other.

00:54:00.639 --> 00:54:05.639
So then, you know, the conversation is, look, if you're writing most of the workflow in Python, why can't you call this R subroutine?

00:54:06.639 --> 00:54:07.639
Because our analysis works in there.

00:54:07.639 --> 00:54:12.639
And if the engineering team wants to reconfigure the ETL in Python, well, that's their prerogative, right?

00:54:13.639 --> 00:54:14.639
They're thinking about the compute time.

00:54:15.639 --> 00:54:23.639
But there shouldn't be sort of a debate about, you know, do you need to change the actual mathematical analysis from one language to another?

00:54:24.639 --> 00:54:27.639
That doesn't feel like a good use of time given the interoperability that's available.

00:54:31.639 --> 00:54:32.639
Sounds good. Thanks.

00:54:33.639 --> 00:54:34.639
Absolutely.

