00:55:02.639 --> 00:55:10.639
You talked a lot about the financial sector having trouble finding qualified staff to bring on full time.

00:55:11.639 --> 00:55:21.639
And what do you see for trends in that type of analysis being available for freelance workers or outside organizations, consultants, things like that?

00:55:22.639 --> 00:55:23.639
If you just kind of comment on that, I'd appreciate it.

00:55:24.639 --> 00:55:25.639
Sure.

00:55:26.639 --> 00:55:30.639
I don't have any stats to speak about the trend on freelancing specifically.

00:55:31.639 --> 00:55:33.639
But generally, I try to think about things from first principles.

00:55:34.639 --> 00:55:39.639
And when a person or a tool does and does not make sense.

00:55:40.639 --> 00:55:43.639
So I'll answer this question kind of the same way that I answered the R versus Python question.

00:55:44.639 --> 00:55:47.639
There are great use cases for when to use somebody who is a freelancer.

00:55:49.639 --> 00:55:52.639
You're usually paying them on a per project or an hourly basis.

00:55:53.639 --> 00:55:56.639
And usually they would be more expensive than a W2 employee.

00:55:57.639 --> 00:56:03.639
And you can usually get them onboarded for that very narrow kind of use case much faster than a W2.

00:56:04.639 --> 00:56:12.639
And so there is a reason to utilize a freelancer, for example, or an outsourced firm when you need to get something accomplished really quickly.

00:56:13.639 --> 00:56:14.639
But it's an in and out kind of task.

00:56:15.639 --> 00:56:17.639
If you're talking about somebody who is a permanent hire.

00:56:18.639 --> 00:56:22.639
Well, there's a legal question about do you want them to be a 10-9 or W2?

00:56:23.639 --> 00:56:26.639
It's actually more of a legal and HR question than a substance question.

00:56:27.639 --> 00:56:32.639
And then finally, if you have a capability that's ultimately going to be core.

00:56:33.639 --> 00:56:39.639
You probably want that to live with your full-time staff who kind of bet their careers on working with you for the long run.

00:56:40.639 --> 00:56:43.639
So in my experience, whether you're outsourcing or freelancing.

00:56:44.639 --> 00:56:49.639
It's great to get initiative going to make sure that the capability is online quickly.

00:56:49.639 --> 00:56:53.639
But then equally have a plan to kind of have some full-time staff.

00:56:54.639 --> 00:56:57.639
Having said that, I don't have a command of the trend of freelance use.

00:56:58.639 --> 00:57:02.639
But I bet if you went to someone like Upwork, they might have some data analysis around that.

