01:00:26.639 --> 01:00:27.639
So I couldn't agree with you more.

01:00:27.639 --> 01:00:30.639
I'm a huge fan of R for financial services applications.

01:00:31.639 --> 01:00:39.639
And I think that there needs to be a sort of intellectual acknowledgement that there is software development and there are good tools for software development.

01:00:40.639 --> 01:00:49.639
And there are tools for finance where you need to get to an analytical result quickly and be able to communicate that easily with other decision makers.

01:00:50.639 --> 01:00:53.639
And I find that R is much better for that second use case.

01:00:53.639 --> 01:00:56.639
So from my standpoint, it's not about what's better R or Python, right?

01:00:57.639 --> 01:01:07.639
They're both great tools, but they have very distinct use cases and they have very underused libraries for calling the subroutines from each other and creating interoperability.

01:01:08.639 --> 01:01:10.639
I think it's much more about that than what is better.

